Author Post


21 Apr 2016 02:15






So, the rewrite (originally from an unknown author) is up. Normally, I like to wait around 24 hours before I start commenting explanations and things, just to make sure that I know people are coming to their own impressions, without my external influence. However, this particular article took more out of me than I thought it would. So, I've worked out a bit of a FAQ that I'll add to over time as questions come in, starting with a number of things that came up during my drafting.

+one!

-one!


Short answer, of course, is that it dropped into the negatives and was in danger of being deleted. However, that's not the whole story. 847 is popular enough that there's no good way to just let it die, anyway. There's lots of fanart of 847, it's a popular article for Youtube readings, someone tried to write a game for it It needed to be kept around, somehow.

But hey, if it's so popular, why the low rating? Well its allure is also its drawback. The picture and article are, to be honest, naively misogynistic. It's a sexy broken female object that runs around attacking women. I don't think the original author meant anything bad by that - they just had the idea of something that was sexycreepy. But in the end, it reduces women to victims and is a literal symbol of objectification itself. Due to the popularity, it had to remain much intact in its form. However, this inherent misogyny had to be acknowledged and addressed. Why attack women? Why does it exist? I turned that in my head and realized that it had to be a story about the horrors of female objectification. And that's what I wrote.

It had to stay sexy. It had to still look like its original picture. It had to still attack women and heal itself that way. But hopefully now, deep in hippocampus, deep in the roiling emotive miasma of your limbic system, it makes sense, and acknowledges that the object is misogynistic in nature.




+picture?

-picture?


The short answer is that it could not be shown to be CC compliant.

The long answer is that anyone could first tell immediately that it's not a photo of a mannequin, but a heavily photoshopped image of a young woman. As evocative as the original is, it's not really up to our standards. However, given its popularity, I couldn't just immediately replace it. I searched high and low for the picture's provenance, and couldn't find anything. However, a member of the Rewrite Team did. The original pre-photoshop picture, it turns out, was of a teenage girl in a seductive pose, and found on a  forum. We just couldn't use it after that.

Of course, that was kind of the point of my version of SCP-847 in the first place.

However, I made sure that my depiction of SCP-847 still, at the end, matched the original picture, no longer in use.




+pictures?

-pictures?


Ah, yes! First things first: they're all photos of real mannequins. Some thought a couple might be sex dolls, but no, they're all mannequins.

Here are the links to the originals (all from Flickr):

The mannequins in the basement:  by dave ungar

The original SCP-847:  by Thomas Hawk

The broken SCP-847:  by Camil Tulcan

Tyler Jensen's SCP-847:  by Jessis Luvr

I tell you, it runs deep.




+object?

-object?


I got this question a lot while having it reviewed. I do have a personal headcanon of precisely what happened in Las Vegas, but that frustrating ambiguity is intentional. After all, if she's a person, then we need to help her, find a way to help her recover. But if it's just an object, it should be locked away, hidden. There's horror in not knowing. You feel a call to action. Part of you wants to save her. Part of you wants to destroy it. And you dare not get this wrong.

But also, I'm going to get on a soapbox and talk further about this for a moment. The other reason I made it as difficult as possible to tell what SCP-847 is, is that no matter what, it has very strongly the aura of a person driven to mental illness from a lifetime of abuse. Victims and survivors of abuse often have difficulty dealing with the emotions from their ordeal, and it can cause them to lash out in very harsh ways. There's a lot of victim-blaming that survivors suffer, as a result. Why did they stay with their abusers for as long as they did? It's over now, can't they just stop crying and cringing? They keep seeking validation, aren't they just asking for more abuse? Many times, it's easy just to turn off compassion for them, and leave them to suffer, assumed to be broken beyond repair.

But they aren't.

We feel that even in the case of a murderous, nonresponsive literal object such as SCP-847, if there's a person inside, there's something worth saving. There's compassion there. I have to strip out so much humanity from SCP-847 just for us to begin to think that maybe it's an object.

No survivor of abuse is an object. Every last one of them is a person, and worthy of compassion. So we have an obligation to help them. Yes, it's not easy. Yes, it hurts. Yes, we might not be up to the task. But it's important to do what we reasonably can. Just. please don't scorn them.

And if you or someone close to you is a survivor who needs help, you can contact me privately and I can get you in touch with groups who can help.



~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

I would like to thank MrWrong, A_Random_Day, Cyantreuse, DrClef, the entire rewrite team, and a couple close female friends who are not members of the SCP community but who are well-acquainted with the horrors of abuse, for reviewing, guiding, encouraging, warning, and advising me throughout this process. Writing this was hard. Painful. But when I started down this direction, I knew how it had to turn out.





